The 5 Most Useful Real-World JOIN Patterns
A) Revenue per user
SELECT u.user_id, u.name, SUM(o.amount) AS revenue
FROM users u
JOIN orders o ON u.user_id = o.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.name;

B) Users with failed payments
SELECT DISTINCT u.user_id, u.name
FROM users u
JOIN orders o ON u.user_id = o.user_id
JOIN payments p ON o.order_id = p.order_id
WHERE p.status = 'FAILED';

C) Orders without payments (data quality check kosam)
SELECT o.order_id
FROM orders o
LEFT JOIN payments p ON o.order_id = p.order_id
WHERE p.payment_id IS NULL;

D) Last order per user
SELECT u.user_id, u.name, MAX(o.created_at) AS last_order
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN orders o ON u.user_id = o.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.name;

E) Top users by spend
SELECT u.user_id, u.name, SUM(o.amount) AS total_spent
FROM users u
JOIN orders o ON u.user_id = o.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.name
ORDER BY total_spent DESC
LIMIT 10;

Common Fresher Pitfalls chudandi:
- Filtering LEFT JOIN in WHERE (turns it into INNER JOIN)
- Missing ON condition (cartesian explosion)
- Using RIGHT JOIN instead of LEFT JOIN
- No indexes on join columns (slow avuthaay queries )
- SELECT * on multi-joins (huge payloads padthaay)
